atlassian-gadgets-publisher-plugin-4.3.9 implements the following endsWidth:
{code:java}
    var indexOf = str.indexOf(postfix);
    return indexOf !== -1 && str.length - postfix.length === indexOf;
 {code}
This implementation is broken, if the search strings occurs multiple times in the string.

So endsWidth("ABA", "A") returns incorrectly false.

This eg. breaks gadets proxy urls (similar to CONFSERVER-53081), if base URL like http://jira.atlassian.com/jira are in use.

A similar broken function is also shipped in strings.js of base jira.

When using the CSV importer, some additional packages are being added to the Logging and Profiling page and stay there until you restart the application. The more imports that are done, more of these lines will show up there.

h3. Example

{code}
com.atlassian.jira.plugins.importer.imports.bulkcreate.engine.BulkCreateDataImporter$ValidableFileImportLoggerThread
{code}
And
{code}
class com.atlassian.jira.plugins.importer.imports.importer.impl.AbstractDataImporter$1Thread[http-nio-9280-exec-20,5,main]
{code}
h2. Steps to reproduce

# Import a CSV file.
# Verify the entries added to the Logging and Profiling page for the existence of similar entries:
{code}
com.atlassian.jira.plugins.importer.imports.bulkcreate.engine.BulkCreateDataImporter$ValidableFileImportLoggerThread
{code}
And
{code}
class com.atlassian.jira.plugins.importer.imports.importer.impl.AbstractDataImporter$1Thread[http-nio-9280-exec-20,5,main]
{code}

h2. Expected results

Nothing gets added there just by using the import functionality of the application.

h2. Actual results

These packages are added.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

First off: I prefer to use the text mode and I would protest if it wasn't there. It's a shame that Atlassian hasn't implemented Markdown natively as part of Jira and that there seems to be no _official_ plugin supporting it. Markdown is one of the reasons I love Bitbucket.org.

Anyway, given that we as users are stuck with the Confluence Wiki Markup (as it was at least called in the past), I am running into problems time and time again. This ticket is about _that_.

I am using all kinds of programming and markup languages and with Jira I am struggling to format something as simple as (in words) "backslash, 'usepackage', opening brace, closing brace" inline. Most of the problems occur when attempting to format something inline, even when something like {{\{noformat\}}} (<- the rendered HTML suggests that the braces are not even part of the <tt> element created by the double-braces) will work.

Case in point:

{noformat}
\usepackage{}
{noformat}

Now let's try to make this properly render inline with Confluence Wiki Syntax:

h2. First attempt

Trying to escape the "special" characters:

{noformat}
{{\\usepackage\{\}}}
{noformat}

... even though the current documentation doesn't even mention the backslash any longer.

Outcome: {{\\usepackage\{\}}}

NB: that line break after "Outcome:" above isn't from me.

h2. Second attempt

Adding a leading backslash:

{noformat}
{{\\\usepackage\{\}}}
{noformat}

Outcome: {{\\\usepackage\{\}}}

h2. Third attempt

... let's at least get those braces to show up somehow:

{noformat}
{{\\\usepackage{{}}}}
{noformat}

Outcome: {{\\\usepackage{{}}}}

... argh. Now the closing brace is no longer part of the monospaced text.

h2. Fourth attempt

... maybe by escaping the closing braces somehow?

{noformat}
{{\\\usepackage{{\}}}
{noformat}

Outcome: {{\\\usepackage{{\}}}

... argh.

h2. Summary

... can we agree that this appears to be an arbitrary/unpredictable outcome? I _really_ hope someone at Atlassian can see how frustrating this user experience is. Since the problem still exists with the Jira version used for this tracker, I assume I needn't give a Jira version. But if it matters: {{v8.1.0#801000-sha1:2e1cd1b}}.

I've been fighting these issues (on and off) since Jira 5.x. And it's not just LaTeX code which cannot be properly formatted inline (which is really a must-have inside bullet lists), it also affects several constructs in C and C++, though I don't remember the issues from the top of my head (and cannot look them up as I don't have access to that Jira instance any longer).

Any chance that the technical audience (as opposed to the mouse-pusher faction) can see that fixed? How about supporting MarkDown as a first-class-citizen in the Jira world, for example?

btw: this is an in-house instance of Jira. Hope this was the correct project I picked. If not, please move the ticket around.

h3. Summary
The restore from Cloud to Server fails with the following message in the UI: 
{quote}
There was a problem restoring ActiveObjects data for the <unknown plugin> plugin. Caught exception with the following message: Column 'jiraschema.PROJECT.ID' is not the same data type as referencing column 'AO_2C4E5C_MAILWHITELISTS.PROJECT_ID' in foreign key 'fk_ao_2c4e5c_mailwhitelists_project_id'. Please check the log for details.
{quote}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Export a backup from Service Desk Cloud.
# Restore the backup into Service Desk Server.

h3. Expected Results
Backup should be restored with no issues. 

h3. Actual Results
The restore fails, the following errors is thrown in the log (example: SQL Server): 
{noformat}
Caused by: com.microsoft.sqlserver.jdbc.SQLServerException: Column 'dbo.PROJECT.ID' is not the same data type as referencing column 'AO_2C4E5C_MAILWHITELISTS.PROJECT_ID' in foreign key 'fk_ao_2c4e5c_mailwhitelists_project_id'.
{noformat}
 
h3. Notes
* This issue is very similar to JRASERVER-67706.
* The problem is caused by a line in *activeobjects.xml*: 
{code:xml|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
    <foreignKey fromTable="AO_2C4E5C_MAILWHITELISTS" fromColumn="PROJECT_ID" toTable="PROJECT" toColumn="ID"/>
{code}

h3.Workaround
The problematic line has to be removed from *activeobjects.xml* file:
{code:xml|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
    <foreignKey fromTable="AO_2C4E5C_MAILWHITELISTS" fromColumn="PROJECT_ID" toTable="PROJECT" toColumn="ID"/>
{code}

The following steps can be used to perform and validate this change:
# Unzip cloud backup
{code:java}
unzip cloudbackup.zip
Archive:  cloudbackup.zip
  inflating: entities.xml
  inflating: activeobjects.xml
{code}
# Expand xml to multiple lines:
{code:java}
xmllint activeobjects.xml --format > activeobjects_fixed.xml && mv activeobjects_fixed.xml activeobjects.xml 
{code}
# Remove the foreign key entry.
# Zip backup back together.
{code:java}
zip -r cloudbackup_fixed.zip activeobjects.xml entities.xml
{code}
# Move the backup to the import directory on the destination instance and perform the import

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-41654].
  {panel}

